args: We've got to get out of here,\nNOW! Or we're all dead!
This can't be the end.\nThis can't be how it happens.
Another torn scrap... It's definitely Douleur.
They've been laid out like breadcrumbs.
And hopefully, at the trail's end...\nYou'd better be more than a pile\nof confetti, you mouthy rag.
They end here. I guess this\nshed is my destination.
*GASP* Finally, I'm a free book again!\nAhhh, the air's so much sweeter outside\nof the slammer.
Heh. Sounds like you're still in one piece.
Yeah, except for all the LITERAL PIECES\nthat were torn out of my PERFECT, STUDLY\nBODY! Look at me! I'm a ragged mess!
Keh heh heh. You poor dear. So, who\ndo we have to thank for turning you into\nDouleur: The Abridged Version?
Don't ask me. I just ended up here outta\nnowhere. Couldn't see the perp on\naccount of all the CLOYING DARKNESS.
I remember the feel of their hands,\nthough. Tiny and smooth. Moisturized.
A child, then. It must be the\ngirl with the handkerchief.

Yeah, cool, handkerchiefs. So absorbent.
Great for mild-to-moderate spills. More
importantly, Cassandra, you mind telling
me what the HELL is going on?!
An echo of some vengeful dead folks'\nmemories? We picked a hell of a vacation\nspot. Okay, so how do we get back out?
＂This village is trapped in a tragedy 40\nyears past.＂ You wanna know what the\nREAL tragedy is? This penmanship. Zing!
I surmise that an event four decades\nback explains why the town stands empty\nnow. It must have claimed countless lives.

And now those victims are the ones
keeping this crazy thrill ride going.
But riddle me this: Why's one of those
spirits dropping hints for you?
The memories of the dead always return\nto the same time. Care to guess where?
The dead don't relive their final moments\nto relish the memory of being alive; they\ndo it because they refuse to accept death.
＂I should have survived.＂\n＂There must have been a way.＂\nThey cling to that possibility.
Few seem to escape this vicious cycle.\nThey relive the agony of death eternally.
Yeesh. I'm starting to see why you'd\nwelcome a little outside help.
Notice how I'm not asking why you're\nweirdly knowledgeable about all this\ndead-people stuff.
Let's just say I've pored over a\nwealth of material on the subject.
More to the point, we're probably about\nto witness the tragedy from 40 years ago\nfirsthand.
If we can get out ahead of it and save the\nvillagers—
It'll dispel their resentment and break\ntheir ties to these final memories.
And to that end, I need to\nask a little favor of you.
I'll just drop my tools off in the shed.\nYou go on ahead to the riverside.
Coast looks clear here.\nSo, what do you need from me?
Check in with the me in the diary from 40\nyears back. I would have made a note of\nany rumors or intel that came my way.
Ahhh, yeah. If it was bad enough, news\nof whatever happened here might have\nreached the castle. Let's see...
＂Day 8, month of the Prismawyrm. Aurelius\nplayed a song for me today. The masculine\nline of his jaw as he sang was—＂
The GERMANE bits. Unless you'd like to\nbecome the ABRIDGED Abridged Version.
Ooooh, sooo scary! ...Ah! Here we go.\n＂Day 13, month of the Blazewyrm.＂

＂Flood took a small village southwest of
the capital, claiming the better half of its
citizens' lives. He's changed his schedule
to make a consolation visit there.＂
＂The day of the disaster, the villagers\ngathered at the riverside for what they call\nthe Festival of Floating Lanterns.＂
I'm just a bit lightheaded.\nCan you tell me when the festival begins?
After sundown, of course. You can't\nenjoy the lanterns till after dark, love.
＂A flash flood struck, brought on by days of\nheavy rains upstream. The village was all\nbut washed away.＂

＂It would have been a tragedy no matter
where it happened, but when I heard the
village's name, I stopped short. It was—＂
...The rest of the page is torn.
Did I...know this place?\nI can't recall anything of the sort.
Senility's a bear, grandma. Zing! Anyway,\nshouldn't we be hurrying down to the river?
So, these are the festival grounds.
Ah, you made it, miss!\nFestival's just about to start.
Mm, I can't wait. I couldn't help but\nnotice, though—isn't the river running\na little fast?
Can't argue that. The rain's been\nnigh-torrential around here as of late.
Then the water level must be high. Seems\ndangerous, doesn't it? It's a shame, but\nperhaps we'd best postpone the festivities.
Hmmm... Better safe than sorry, I suppose.\nEspecially with little ones around.
Not happening. The festival's been held on\nthis day as long as I've walked the earth!
Tradition is important, to be sure.\nI'd argue safety is even more paramount.
Today's the day, and there's not a dang\nthing anyone can say to change that!\n
But if we don't stop this—
You're actin' awful strange, child. You\nneed to come rest a spell at my house?
(I don't suppose pressing the point\nhere will make any difference.)
No. It wasn't my place to interfere.
You got a plan B, Cassandra? Because\nwe're whitewater rafting our way to a\nmassacre here.
When the flood comes, I'll erect a barrier\nto shield the villagers. It's the only way.
You're gonna block a natural disaster big\nenough to wipe a town off the map?\nAlone?
I understand the risk.\nBut this is the only chance we've got.
